{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509015"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:12:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:12:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11372"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11372"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.37,0.34,0.1,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29174"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4017"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15333"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"262"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8228"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17603"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/29174"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman presents with a palpable, asymptomatic 2cm left breast lump. She has never had any other breast problems and there is no family history of breast disease. Examination of both breasts is normal, apart form the 2cm oval shaped, smooth and mobile lump in her left breast. Ultrasound demonstrates a well circumscribed homogenous solid mass. She has a repeat ultrasound in six months later and now the lesion has increased to 3cm. It still appears as a well circumscribed homogenous solid mass without complex features.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound surveillance in six months","Ultrasound-guided fine needle aspiration","Ultrasound-guided core biopsy","Surgical excision","Wide local excision and sentinel lymph node biopsy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOn initial presentation this patient has a presumed simple fibroadenoma - it is a mobile well-circumscribed solid mass in a young woman. These are benign tumours of glandular and fibrous tissue, therefore it is appropriate to either monitor with short term surveillance (3-6 months), perform a core biopsy for diagnosis (for women over the age of 25), or excise (especially if symptomatic or causing patient distress).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the lesion has significantly increased in size (1cm) within a short time period, therefore further action needs to be taken. This patient requires an \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound-guided core biopsy.\u003C/strong\u003E If it confirms a fibroadenoma then the lesion can be excised around the capsule, so minimising cosmetic deformity. The predominant concern is that this lesion may be a phyllodes tumour, which can be benign or malignant. These have similar ultrasound features to a fibroadenoma however their differentiating clinical feature is that they are a rapidly growing breast mass. If it is shown to be a phyllodes tumour on the biopsy, then excising the lesion with an additional cuff of normal breast tissue around the lesion, would be the recommended treatment. So knowing what it is before surgery alters the surgical plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ewide local excision\u003C/strong\u003E (\u0026gt;1cm margin) would be indicated for borderline or malignant phyllodes tumours, however a sentinel lymph node biopsy is not required. A core biopsy is performed rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Efine needle aspiration (FNA) \u003C/strong\u003Ebecause of the high proportion of fibrous tissue. Further \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound surveillance in six months\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate, given the increase in size.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Fibroadenomas that significantly increase in size on surveillance raises concern for phyllodes tumour and require excision to exclude malignant change."],"references":["Brennan M, Houssami N, French J. Management of benign breast conditions, Part 2 - breast lumps and lesions. Australian Family Physician. 2005; 34(4): 253-5","Amin AL, Purdy AC, Mattingly JD, Kong AL, Termuhlen PM. Benign breast disease. Surg Clin North Am. 2013 Apr;93(2):299-308"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15333"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11372"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/15333"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-10-17T19:15:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-22T11:51:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4017"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29174"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree